&gt; &gt; &gt; A much simpler approach is to create a test case extension
&gt; &gt; &gt; which
&gt; &gt; &gt; delegates it&#39;s execution to a session bean.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Why is it simpler? That&#39;s exactly Cactus&#39;s approach! :-). ATM cactus
&gt; &gt; only provides Filter, Servlet and Jsp extensions but we are working
on
&gt; &gt; providing EJB redirectors (session beans, MDB, EB).
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m glad to hear that _will_be_ Cactus approach  :-)
&gt; I evaluated Cactus before I decided to write ServerTestCase and was
&gt; disappointed it didn&#39;t support what I wanted to do.
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; I would love to be
&gt; &gt; able to work with you on that if you&#39;re interested! It seems we
could
&gt; &gt; easily integrate your solution in Cactus :-)
&gt; 
&gt; Yes. I have made some improvements since the junit.org version. I
could
&gt; send
&gt; you the updated source, or I could integrate myself i guess.

What would be great would be for you to join the cactus dev mailing list
and start submitting ideas/patches/docs/whatever. That would help a lot!
I will definitely help you to perform the integration.

If you&#39;re interested let&#39;s continue this discussion on the cactus-dev
mailing list (see http://jakarta.apache.org/cactus/mailinglist.html for
subscribing).

Thanks a lot
-Vincent

&gt; 
&gt; --
&gt; Jon S Bratseth
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; &gt; There is a package which provides this at
&gt; &gt; &gt; http://www.junit.org/junit/download/ServerTestCase.zip
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; cool. Maybe we can join forces.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; To use it, just deploy the session bean and extends ServerTestCase
&gt; &gt; instead
&gt; &gt; &gt; of TestCase for tests you want to run inside the server.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Cool. Again, that&#39;s exactly in the same way as Cactus does it.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; The tests will behave like the client/standalone tests, so there
will
&gt; &gt; only
&gt; &gt; &gt; be one test suite to manage and there&#39;s no need to re-create all
the
&gt; &gt; &gt; features mentioned below specially for the server-side tests.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Yes, but I don&#39;t see how you test your web layer with your solution.
If
&gt; &gt; I remember correctly that was what I was answering to :-). In any
case
&gt; &gt; you don&#39;t need to care as Cactus is hiding this for you. EJBs are
&gt; &gt; well-defined components and as such are much easier to unit test
than
&gt; &gt; web components. Actually if you have remote EJBs, you don&#39;t even
need to
&gt; &gt; have a session bean redirector, which is even simpler ... :-)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; ...Yeah, I know I&#39;m lagging somewhat  :-)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I don&#39;t think so :-)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; -Vincent
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; --
&gt; &gt; &gt; Jon S Bratseth
